# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1877
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The **16 May 1877 crisis**, or more simply the **Seize Mai**, was a political crisis and institutional crisis that occurred in France during the Third Republic.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It pitted the President of the Republic, Marshal Patrice de Mac Mahon, a convinced monarchist, against the republican majority that had emerged from the 1876 legislative elections.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The events took place in a turbulent political context.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In the Chamber of Deputies, the republicans led by Léon Gambetta, who sought to break with the lingering Orléanist spirit of the regime, attempted to impose their demands and fiercely opposed ultramontanism.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Marshal de Mac Mahon, who reproached the Jules Simon government for its lack of firmness, dismissed it on 16 May 1877.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] From then on, the situation escalated: left-wing deputies met to sign the manifesto of the 363, which condemned the president's attitude; Mac Mahon in turn appointed the duke Albert de Broglie as head of a government that marked the return of the ordre moral.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Mac Mahon dissolved the Chamber on 25 June 1877, but the subsequent legislative elections in October confirmed the republican majority.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Initially, President Mac Mahon refused to yield and rumours of an alleged coup d'état circulated, but he eventually submitted and acknowledged his political defeat on 13 December 1877 by recalling the republican Jules Dufaure to the presidency of the Council.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The significance of this political crisis was immense, as it definitively shaped the practical operation of the institutions.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It set aside the conservative interpretation of the constitutional laws of 1875, in favour of a strictly republican interpretation of the Constitution in which the government is accountable only to parliament, which invests and dismisses it.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The head of state's renunciation of his constitutional prerogatives henceforth placed the executive power under the domination of the legislative power, while the practice of the right of dissolution, although enshrined in the Constitution, disappeared.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Furthermore, the 16 May crisis marked the transition between two eras of French democracy and strengthened the rooting in people's minds of a still-nascent republican regime, dashing the hopes of the various monarchist currents of seeing a new restoration established.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] An event relatively little studied by historiography, the Seize Mai has left some traces in popular culture and marks an important date for republicans, who regularly referred to it in their political struggles.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It was also in the context of this crisis that Victor Hugo published his *Histoire d'un crime*.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 4 September 1870, amid the ruins of the Second Empire defeated by Prussia, the republic was proclaimed.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In order to stem the insurrection and rule out the prospect of a revolutionary government, the republican deputies agreed on the formation of a Government of National Defense.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] A series of military disasters and the suffering by the people during the siege of Paris ultimately swept away the cabinet despite the determination of Léon Gambetta.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Until 1877, monarchists and republicans engaged in an intense political struggle for control of the institutions and for the legal definition to be given to them.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] After the large victory of the monarchists in the legislative elections of 8 February 1871, Adolphe Thiers was appointed "head of the executive power of the French Republic", pending the signature of peace and the restoration of order.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Under the leadership of the head of state, who officially received the title of President of the Republic after the passage of the Loi Rivet, the regime gradually moved toward a conservative republicanism.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In fact, the monarchists, while awaiting a pretender to the throne, postponed the drafting of a definitive constitution and the provisional institutions evolved slowly, while the republicans advanced in every by-election.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Hopes for a monarchical restoration resurfaced after Thiers's resignation in 1873 and the election of Patrice de Mac Mahon, whose political ambition appeared limited to the return of the king and to "moral order".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] However, the intransigence of the Count of Chambord, leader of the Legitimist monarchists who demanded the adoption of the white flag in place of the tricolour flag, ruled out any possibility of a royalist restoration in the short term.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The republican principle of the regime appeared definitively established on 30 January 1875 by the adoption, by a majority of one vote (353 against 352), of the Wallon amendment.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The constitutional laws that followed, passed between February and July 1875, were the result of a compromise between monarchists and republicans and established a parliamentary regime with a strong executive.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The President of the Republic was its main actor and enjoyed extensive powers.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In addition to the armed forces and the right of pardon, he appointed and dismissed ministers who were responsible to the Chamber of Deputies, with the possibility of dissolving the latter subject to the conforming opinion of the Senate.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In legislative matters, the president shared the initiative of laws with the two Chambers.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It was his duty to promulgate them after their vote in Parliament, and then to ensure and oversee their execution.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Furthermore, since the president was irresponsible, each of his decisions had to be countersigned by a minister who assumed responsibility for it before the Chamber.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The government appointed by the president was therefore theoretically accountable both to the president and to the deputies, which made it, according to Professor Marcel Morabito, the "true centre of the opposition between the constituted organs that strive to weigh on its orientation".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Following the elections of 30 January 1876, the Senate retained a narrow conservative majority with 151 seats for the monarchists and Bonapartists against 149 for the republicans.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In contrast, the legislative elections of February–March 1876 confirmed the trend seen in the most recent by-elections and gave an absolute majority to the republicans, who held nearly 350 sieges in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The collapse of the conservatives was experienced as a disaster by President Mac Mahon, who appointed Jules Dufaure to head a government composed of moderate monarchists and centre-left republicans.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] A conservative republican, Dufaure came under pressure from the deputies and his ministry constantly sought compromises.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 9 December, accused by the republican majority of supporting the president's opposition to the amnesty of the Communards, he resigned.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] To form the new government, Mac Mahon turned to Senator Jules Simon, who described himself as "profoundly republican and profoundly conservative" .
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Close to Adolphe Thiers, Simon had the advantage in the president's eyes of being clearly further to the left than his predecessor while being a notorious opponent of Léon Gambetta, the leader of the republican majority .
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The expression "Seize Mai" does not refer only to the events of that day, 16 May 1877, but to the whole of a period "politically agitated and deeply troubled" that ended seven months later with the submission of the head of state.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] For Jules Simon, as for his predecessor, the position was delicate between a monarchist Senate, a conservative president and a republican Chamber.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The new President of the Council gave pledges to the left by purging the upper administration (prefects and magistrates), which earned him the hostility of the marshal, but the republicans made increased demands and Gambetta relentlessly tried to put him in difficulty.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 4 May 1877, from the rostrum of the Chamber, Gambetta reproached Jules Simon for having lacked firmness in the face of ultramontane manoeuvres.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] He denounced "clerical evil [...] deeply infiltrated into what are called the ruling classes of the country" and ended his speech by repeating a phrase inspired by his journalist friend Alphonse Peyrat, "Clericalism?
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] His motion was adopted without Simon opposing it.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 16 May 1877, early in the morning, the president reacted sharply to reading the *Journal officiel de la République française* which reported the previous day's debate in the Chamber.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] A few moments later, the secretary-general of the President of the Republic, Emmanuel d'Harcourt, read the text and, understanding the gravity of the situation, persuaded Mac Mahon to send an usher to retrieve the letter, but in vain.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Disavowed, Jules Simon immediately tendered his resignation to the head of state, even though he had not been put in the minority in the Chamber.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The president accepted it, declaring among other things that he would "rather be overthrown than remain under the orders of Moscow".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Jules Simon then attended the funerals of the former minister Ernest Picard and then those of the former deputy Taxile Delord, where he informed his various ministers and the numerous politicians present of the situation; they were outraged by the presidential move.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] A meeting of the Republican Left, already scheduled for 3 PM on the Boulevard des Capucines, was opened to the other political groups.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It ultimately brought together 200 parliamentarians including a few senators.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Marshal Mac Mahon recalled the duke Albert de Broglie to the presidency of the Council and the latter formed a right-wing government that marked the return to the moral order.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] By appointing a ministry in line with his views, against the opinion of the deputies, the president offered a dualist reading of the constitution: for him the government was as much his emanation as that of the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On the morning of 17 May 1877, while the press echoed the crisis, a large crowd gathered shouting "Vive la République!", "Vive Gambetta!", in front of the Gare Saint-Lazare from where the parliamentarians' trains departed for Versailles.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] He thus intended to show that the crisis opposed two different interpretations of the constitutional laws but that it was in no way a struggle between a majority and an individual.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The motion defended by Gambetta received 347 votes against 149, the great majority of the deputies of the centre left having joined the other republicans.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The composition of the new government was announced on 18 May 1877.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In accordance with the provisions laid down in the Constitution, the president also decided to prorogue the chambers for one month, by decree.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Immediately after the close of the sitting, the republican deputies gathered in the office of Senator Émile de Marcère at the Hôtel des Réservoirs.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Léon Gambetta proposed drafting an address to the country that would constitute "an act of protest against the policy irregular, if not in the letter, at least in the spirit of the Constitution".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] A deputy then mentioned the Address of the 221 that had led to the dissolution of the Chamber of Deputies by King Charles X in 1830.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Gambetta immediately took up the idea because he believed that such an address must bring about the definitive fall of the conservatives: "Imagine what the reflux of this ocean of universal suffrage will be, pushing before it and casting forever onto the shore all the wreckage of the Ancien Régime".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The text, written for the most part by his friend Eugène Spuller, took the name of manifesto of the 363, from the number of deputies who added their signatures.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It affirmed that "France wants the Republic" and that "she will show by her calm, her patience, her resolution, that an incorrigible minority cannot wrest from her the government of herself".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The three left-wing groups in the Senate for their part added a similar declaration.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Local elected officials were affected by these measures: 1,743, or 4% of mayors, and 1,334 adjuncts were dismissed, and 613 city councils were dissolved.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] 133 secretaries-general and 170 prefectural councillors were also transferred or dismissed.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In whatever form the lie may appear, as soon as it is uttered publicly, it can be punished".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Prosecutors as well as justices of the peace were in turn removed.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Taking advantage of their parliamentary immunity, the republican deputies waged the fight by organising public meetings in their constituencies, but also in the press.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On Gambetta's initiative, a "general committee of resistance and propaganda" brought together newspapers of all tendencies and met in the offices of his own daily newspaper, *La République française*.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The republicans insisted above all on the fight against clericalism rather than on the constitutional question, which was less likely to arouse public opinion.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The conservatives themselves seemed divided, the Orléanists and the Legitimists appearing more reserved than the Bonapartists regarding the appropriateness of President Mac Mahon's initiative.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Abroad, the crisis provoked numerous reactions and, with the exception of the Vatican, European newspapers were unanimous in defending the parliamentarism of the republicans or denouncing clerical manoeuvres.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 16 June 1877, one month after its prorogation, the Chamber met again but the marshal immediately dissolved it, in accordance with Article 5 of the law of 25 February 1875.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] That same day, he asked the Senate for its "conforming opinion", as the Constitution provided.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Deputy Gustave Gailly replied: pointing at Adolphe Thiers, he exclaimed "The liberator of the territory, there he is!", which aroused the enthusiasm of the left and the centre.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Gambetta then delivered a speech lasting more than two hours in which he notably accused the Vatican of having "engineered the whole operation of 16 May".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The motion of no confidence, proposed by the presidents of the left-wing groups, confirmed the unity of the republicans in the crisis: it was adopted on 19 June by 363 votes to 158.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Confident of his camp's imminent success, Gambetta declared: "We are leaving as 363, we shall return as 400".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The Senate's opinion was given on 22 June: by 149 votes to 130, it proved favourable to the presidential will.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The Chamber was dissolved three days later, on 25 June.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The official electoral campaign did not open until three months after the dissolution, on 22 September 1877; but the preceding months were highly agitated politically and this campaign is described as one "of the most vehement" in the history of France.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In the name of "the struggle between order and disorder", President Mac Mahon personally committed himself to the electoral battle and multiplied trips to the provinces.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] As early as 9 June, in order to secure the Senate decision on the dissolution of the Chamber, he had reached an agreement with the Legitimists, guaranteeing them numerous constituencies in exchange for their support and pledging to leave power definitively at the end of his septennat.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 3 July, the Duke of Broglie declared that candidates favourable to the head of state could use a white poster bearing the words "Candidat du gouvernement du maréchal de Mac-Mahon", in the manner of the official candidacies of the Second Empire.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In a communiqué, the president defended these candidacies and hinted that he might attempt to resist if the election result were unfavourable to him: "In the event of hostile elections, France would become for Europe an object of distrust.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] As for me, my duty would grow with the peril.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] I shall remain to defend, with the support of the Senate, the conservative interests".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In his various speeches, Mac Mahon denounced radicalism and accused the left of running the risk of war for the country.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] He published a new address to the French on 19 September 1877, in which he proclaimed himself in solidarity with the de Broglie cabinet and accused the "363" of wanting a Chamber that would be a replica of the National Convention of 1792.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] At the same time, the government multiplied judicial proceedings against newspaper titles or newspaper sellers and the repression by the prefects intensified: nearly 2,000 bars were closed, as well as several Masonic lodges.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Faced with the president's official candidates, the republicans displayed their unity.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Adolphe Thiers and Léon Gambetta proved the most combative.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Republican newspapers launched subscriptions, increased their circulation and relied on railway workers and commercial travellers to ensure distribution throughout the country.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] An electoral committee was created, composed of 18 deputies representing all republican tendencies, from Georges Clemenceau to Jules Ferry, and other committees were created on the same model at the level of each canton.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The latter delivered a speech in Lille on 15 August 1877 whose peroration has remained famous.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Acclaimed by the audience, he declared to the president and his supporters: "When France has made her sovereign voice heard, believe it well, gentlemen, it will be necessary to submit or resign".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] This formula was immediately reprinted in *La République française* and the Council of Ministers decided to prosecute the speaker, who was no longer protected by parliamentary immunity, and his newspaper, for insulting the head of state.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] This decision was criticised even in the conservative camp, which feared that the trial would give too much publicity to the republican candidate.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Gambetta, tried in absentia on 11 September by the correctional tribunal of the Seine, was sentenced to three months in prison and a fine of 2,000 francs.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Confident of his re-election, he immediately appealed, the second judgment being able to take place only after the ballot.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The death of Adolphe Thiers on 3 September was exploited by the republicans, the "363" gathering around the family of the deceased during the funeral which no official attended on 8 September.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] This sudden disappearance, however, tempered the optimism of the republicans who had envisaged the return of Thiers to the presidency of the Republic in the event of electoral victory and resignation of the marshal.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It was the name of Jules Grévy that replaced it, despite the disagreements that persisted between the latter and Gambetta.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] At the end of September, François-Auguste Mignet published a posthumous manifesto by Thiers in which the former president recalled the absolute necessity of the Republic to avoid civil war.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Just as several ministers of the Broglie cabinet were closely associated with the economic world, numerous members of the centre left held seats as directors in the largest companies in the key sectors of the French economy, particularly banks, railways, mining and metallurgy.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The latter, in addition to their financial power, had all the greater influence because they controlled numerous titles in the liberal press.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Although these newspapers could not claim high circulation, their impact was decisive on the evolution of the regime insofar as they were read not only by politicians but also among economic decision-makers, bankers, stockbrokers or major industrialists.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] However, most economic elites clearly committed themselves in favour of the 36 Republican candidates because they considered the coup of the Seize Mai as "a factor of disorder contrary to the smooth running of the economy".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The *Journal des débats* referred in this regard to "an eloquent lesson in political immorality".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Throughout the campaign, the liberal press echoed the concern of business circles about the economic slowdown caused by the presidential coup, after several years of calm and prosperity, and many of their representatives provided material and financial support to the republicans.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] For example, Léon Say offered 25,000 francs for the formation of the Left Electoral Committee, while major entrepreneurs such as Jean Dollfus, Alfred Koechlin-Schwartz or Camille Risler sat on local electoral committees.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] It was not until 22 September 1877 that the Council of Ministers set the legislative elections for 14 October and the meeting of the Chamber for 7 November.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In the first round, only 15 of the 531 constituencies remained unfilled.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The victory of the republicans was undeniable, but it did not have the scale anticipated: they then counted only 321 elected, far from the 405 predicted by Gambetta a few weeks earlier.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In a letter addressed the next day to Princess Lise Troubetzkoy, the latter denounced the "threats of corruption, excesses of all kinds, overturned ballot boxes, bought and falsified votes, in short more odious acts committed in three months than the Empire had perpetrated in twenty years" .
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In reality, the progress of the conservatives, who gained 50 seats, was explained mainly by the mobilisation of their electorate, with abstention falling from 25% in the 1876 elections to less than 20% in 1877.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In the second round, on 28 October, the conservatives won 11 seats more, and although the republicans ultimately had a large majority, with 323 elected, they led the right by just under 800,000 votes.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] As soon as the election results were known, President Mac Mahon considered resigning, urged in this direction by some of his close associates such as his secretary Emmanuel d'Harcourt, but he gave up the idea.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The de Broglie government, disavowed at the polls, remained in place pending the cantonal elections of 4 November.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In the meantime, Mac Mahon multiplied consultations and considered dissolving the Chamber of Deputies once again, but such a decision would sound like a rejection of the nation's verdict.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Furthermore, the President of the Senate, Gaston d'Audiffret-Pasquier, informed him that, this time, the upper chamber would not give its agreement and advised him to accept a parliamentary government.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 10 November, they declared the Chamber constituted and two days later re-elected Jules Grévy to its presidency, while his brother Albert Grévy proposed the creation of an inquiry commission on illegal acts committed since 16 May.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Composed of 35 deputies, it was accepted by 312 votes to 205 and appointed on 14 October.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The Duke of Broglie sought the Senate's support to reject the commission, but Audiffret-Pasquier informed him that, since a decision to create an inquiry commission was not a law, the upper chamber could not oppose it.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The de Broglie cabinet finally submitted its resignation on the evening of 17 November.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] At an impasse, Mac Mahon appointed one of his close associates to the presidency of the Council, General de Rochebouët.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] No parliamentarian was a member of this cabinet which, in the president's mind, was nothing other than a "business ministry" whose sole mission was to handle current affairs.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The Chamber of Deputies responded immediately by voting a motion of no confidence against a cabinet which, in its eyes, "is the negation of the rights of the nation and of parliamentary rights".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] This motion was largely accepted, by 325 votes to 208, but the government refused to resign.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The tension increased all the more as rumours of a coup d'État spread.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The anger of the republicans redoubled when the president considered the appointment of the Orléanist senator and former minister Anselme Batbie.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The choice of this new conservative government against the republican majority appeared as the president's last attempt to recover his authority and took on the appearance of a real coup d'État.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Once appointed President of the Council, Batbie would have proclaimed the state of siege, had the republican leaders arrested, levied taxes by decree, organised new elections and a plebiscite.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The implementation of this project took shape around 27 and 28 November and rumours spoke of a summons to Paris of the army corps commanders for 10 December, General de Rochebouët having ordered them to stand ready.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On the other hand, the army's support for a coup d'État was by no means guaranteed.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Since 1872, with its ranks based on conscription, republican sentiment had been growing among the military as it took root in the French population.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] In 1877, about 50% of the generals were monarchist in opinion against 39% liberals and republicans, and the proportion was reversed among the colonels with 36.5% monarchists against 45.5% republicans or liberals.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] At the beginning of December, Léon Gambetta met with General de Galliffet to ensure his support for the republic, and several generals spontaneously placed themselves at his disposal, such as Justin Clinchant, Jean-Baptiste Campenon or Jean-Joseph Farre.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Faced with the impossibility of forming a cabinet to his liking, Mac Mahon considered resigning but his close associates dissuaded him again, both to protect themselves and to avoid a total victory for the republicans.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] On 13 December 1877, President Mac Mahon finally submitted to the election results and recalled Jules Dufaure to form a government dominated by moderate republicans of the centre left but which also included some close to Gambetta such as Charles de Freycinet at Public Works.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Gambetta also imposed the presence of William Waddington at Foreign Affairs, despite the reservations of the head of state who was consulted only for the War portfolio, awarded to his former aide-de-camp Jean-Louis Borel, the only apolitical and conservative member of the new cabinet.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Other close associates of the president were removed from their responsibilities: the prefect of police was dismissed as was Mac Mahon's chief of staff, Emmanuel d'Harcourt, who, at the request of the republicans, had no replacement.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Finally, General Ducrot, whom the deputies accused of having too openly conspired in favour of a coup d'État, was relieved of his command of the 8th Army Corps.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The next day, the President of the Republic addressed a message to parliament that sounded like a political capitulation.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Mac Mahon first acknowledged that dissolution could not be a normal way of governing a country and concluded by saying: "The Constitution of 1875 founded a parliamentary Republic by establishing my irresponsibility, while instituting the joint and individual responsibility of the ministers.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] Thus are determined our respective duties and rights.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] The independence of the ministers is the condition of their responsibility. [...] These principles, drawn from the Constitution, are those of my government".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] For the historian Jean-Marc Guislin, "The hesitations and divisions of the conservatives, the hostility of business circles and the reluctance of the army led the Marshal to submit.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p01] He also encountered the firmness and resolution of the country won over to the Republic".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In his statement to the Chamber, President Mac Mahon turned towards the future and affirmed that "the end of this crisis will be the starting point of a new prosperity".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The Universal Exhibition, inaugurated on 1 May 1878 in Paris and which attracted nearly six million visitors, was intended to show the recovery of France and its nascent Republic to the eyes of the world, while parliamentary work was suspended so as not to give a spectacle of division.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Supported by Gambetta, the President of the Council Jules Dufaure showed pragmatism to reassure public opinion as well as the political class and his government initiated major projects such as the Freycinet Plan, a vast public works programme that won strong support.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The definitive break between Mac Mahon and the republicans nevertheless occurred over the question of the purge of the army administration, demanded by Jules Ferry and Gambetta.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The president was also indignant when the minister Émile de Marcère presented for his signature a decree providing for the revocation, transfer or retirement of 82 mayors.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] At the same time, the republicans continued their progress: the Chamber itself invalidated 70 elections on the pretext of clerical or political pressure and, following the by-elections, their number of deputies approached 400.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] On 5 January 1879, the republicans also won the Senate elections, the logical consequence of their victory in the municipal elections of 1877, and obtained the majority in the upper chamber.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The president, deprived of all institutional support, preferred to resign on 30 January 1879 after refusing to sign the decree removing command from about ten generals.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] With the election of the latter, the republicans now dominated all components of power.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Elected to the presidency of the Chamber, Léon Gambetta exhorted the deputies: "We can, we must all, at the present time, feel that the combats have had their day.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Our Republic, finally emerged victorious from the melee of parties, must enter the organic and creative period".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] While the historian Odile Rudelle speaks of the "absolute Republic" to describe the years that mark the definitive conquest of the regime by the republicans, Vincent Duclert calls it the "Republic of the republicans" .
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] For the philosopher Jacques Bouveresse, the 16 May crisis is not a mere constitutional debate but the consecration of the republican conception of the future which consists not only in founding a new constitutional regime, but in laying the foundations of a new society.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] President Mac Mahon then appears as a scapegoat whose moral order government and dualist reading of the Constitution amount to an "irremissible crime against democracy", far more than the massacre of the Communards during the Bloody Week.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] As the historian Jean-Marie Mayeur points out, 16 May coup reflects the desire of the "elites of old France" to preserve their influence and that of the Church on society at the expense of the promotion of "the new layer".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The historian Raymond Huard considers that from this date, "the shadow of the 2 December was thus tending to fade".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The republicans who, traditionally, embodied the threat of disorder, now benefit from popular support and present themselves as guarantors of the institutions, even though their most radical adversaries threaten to use force against them.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] According to Jérôme Grévy, "so as not to risk destroying their image as a governmental party patiently built over six years, the republicans must refuse any temptation of violent action, even if they are sure of their right".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Throughout the period, they distinguished themselves by the calm, resolution and determination they displayed, and as early as 16 May, Gambetta warned his political family against any untimely outburst.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The 16 May 1877 crisis thus testifies to the reversal of political fronts.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] During the electoral campaign, the major titles of the liberal press such as *La Semaine financière* and the *Journal des débats* relayed the concern of business circles and associated the moral order with disorder, while praising the Republic as a guarantee of stability.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The republicans also denounced the risk of war that a clerical policy would entail, in reference to the threats that Chancellor Bismarck had uttered in 1873 when he stated that France's political alignment with the Vatican would make her Germany's sworn enemy.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] It was over a question of a religious nature that the crisis broke out at the beginning of May, with the republicans denouncing the pressures of the Church, long accused of being favourable to a monarchical restoration, and the period ultimately reinforced the antagonism between the two camps.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] While the episcopate remained largely in the background, many priests engaged in a most virulent campaign.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The historian Arnaud-Dominique Houte reports that foreign caricaturists then took to representing Mac Mahon as a puppet manipulated by priests.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] This intrusion of the clergy into the electoral campaign tended to reinforce the anticlericalism of the republicans, with the argument of clerical intervention moreover regularly put forward by the latter to justify the invalidation of certain elections.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] After the president's submission, the appointment of a Protestant to Foreign Affairs in the person of William Waddington demonstrated the republican desire to provide a guarantee of neutrality in diplomatic affairs regarding religious matters.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The historian Jean-François Chanet considers that the Seize Mai marks the transition between two eras of French democracy.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The president remained an influential figure but devoid of real powers.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The Third Republic then slid from a dualist parliamentarism to a monist parliamentarism, in other words a regime of assembly, which ratified the customary drift of the presidential function according to the constitutionalist Éric Ghérardi.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Thus the Seize Mai led to the weakening of the executive power in favour of the legislative power and, in French political culture, it became "a symbolic date and a reference for subsequent republican defence struggles".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The right of dissolution, although enshrined in the constitutional texts and maintained by the republicans during the revision of August 1884, became after the Seize Mai and for several generations of politicians the symbol of an authoritarian danger.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The socialist Léon Blum called it a "legalised coup d'État" while the lawyer and former minister César Campinchi popularised the expression "As long as Mac Mahon is dead, the Chamber will not be dissolved" to express the concerted refusal of its use.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Retained in the Constitution of the Fourth Republic, the right of dissolution remained theoretical until the President of the Council Edgar Faure resorted to it on 29 November 1955 to resolve the crisis opened by the overthrow of his ministry.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Despite the fundamental role of the 16 May crisis in the definitive advent of the Republic, its historiography is sparse.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] While the Seize Mai is frequently mentioned in general works devoted to the early years of the Third Republic, by historians such as Daniel Halévy, Odile Rudelle, Jérôme Grévy or Jean-Marie Mayeur, as well as in biographies devoted to its protagonists, it is rarely the subject of a detailed study.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In 1965, Fresnette Pisani-Ferry published with Éditions Robert Laffont, *Le coup d'État manqué du 16 mai 1877*, while on 16 November 2007, under the direction of Jean-Marc Guislin, a study day was devoted to it at University of Lille III.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Numerous articles and chapters in university works are nevertheless devoted to it.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In 1986, Michel Winock provided a detailed account in his narrative of the political crises of contemporary French history, *La fièvre hexagonale*, and the same year, Guy Thuillier devoted a short thirteen-page study to its possible origins.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Two years later, the sociologist Willy Pelletier spoke on the question at a colloquium devoted to the presidential institution.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In 2002, Jean-Marc Guislin studied the event more particularly through the career of the minister Auguste Paris whose abundant correspondence with his wife he analyses.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] These two events are perceived as exceptional, that is to say that they mark "refer to a turning point in political life sufficiently identifiable without the need to indicate the precise date" according to Jean-François Chanet.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] All historians agree in recognising the importance of the Seize Mai in the political and institutional history of the country.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] For Philippe Levillain, this crisis "is part of the republican annals".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] He specifies that, "intended and experienced as a decisive trial of strength on the definition of conservatism, it had cascading consequences on republican mentalities and its effect was considerable on the behaviour of the rights".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Jean-Marc Guislin for his part describes it as a "neuralgic" period.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In 1877, the Third Republic was still living under the royalist threat and in the memory of the 2 December 1851 coup d'état, so that, for the republicans, "the holders of executive power are in principle suspected of seeking to increase their prerogatives to remain in power".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] It is for this reason that "French historiographical and political tradition has made the Seize-Mai the threat of a coup d'État", as the historian Claude Nicolet asserts.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In many respects, the course of events in 1877 indeed reproduced the process of 1851 that led to the establishment of the Second Empire and the republican historiography that immediately took shape imposed for a vision of the Seize-Mai as a coup de force intended to bring down the Republic.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] More than the coup d'État of 2 December, Mac Mahon's initiative recalled the dismissal in October 1849 by President Bonaparte of the Barrot government, invested with the confidence of the National Assembly, and its replacement by the Hautpoul government favourable to him.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Furthermore, Thierry Truel affirms that the speed with which the Broglie cabinet was formed suggests that the president's coup de force was premeditated.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In 1877, the atmosphere of a coup d'État was all the more perceptible because the Bonapartists explicitly invited the president to take action, as evidenced by the articles of Paul de Cassagnac in *Le Pays* which demanded the state of siege and exceptional laws.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Mac Mahon himself, in his statements, reinforced the ambiguity of the situation.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] I cannot become the instrument of radicalism, nor abandon the post where the Constitution has placed me".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Furthermore, the appointment of authoritarian Bonapartists such as Fourtou to the Interior, the revocations of elected officials or magistrates, and the dissolution of municipal councils were immediately denounced as "the return of the tyrannical acts of the Empire".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] However, the course of the 16 May crisis presents no character of illegality or violence, two criteria determining the notion of coup d'État.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In the first place, as Emmanuel Cherrier notes, "physical violence is nowhere and at no time employed, and there is no seizure of power by force or the threat of force, no troop movements nor arrest of republican leaders".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] On the other hand, all the presidential and governmental acts of the period are established within the limits strictly defined by law.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] As Thierry Truel notes, "most of the dispatches sent to the prefects [...] are intended to remind them of the legal frameworks within which they can act, without falling under the blade of possible legal actions brought by republican opponents".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The crisis results above all from a difference in interpretation of the constitutional laws which still retained a certain ambiguity in 1877.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] For Emmanuel Cherrier, "the Seize-Mai is therefore also a controversy as to the monist or dualist responsibility of the government".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The letter addressed by Mac Mahon therefore has no unconstitutional character, and even more, the president does not feel he is carrying out a coup d'État by taking this initiative: since it is up to him to appoint ministers, he believes he can also revoke them outright.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] By qualifying the action of President Mac Mahon as a coup d'État, the republicans sought above all to discredit him in the eyes of public opinion.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Three days after the coup of 16 May, *La Revue politique et littéraire* announced that the writer was working on a *Histoire du coup d'État* to appear in October and simultaneously in French, English, German and Italian.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] From then on, while preparing the edition of his work, Victor Hugo led the fight in the Senate where he organised two meetings a week with left-wing senators and where he delivered a virulent speech against the dissolution.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The first volume of *Histoire d'un crime* appeared on 1 October, two weeks before the first round of the legislative elections, and achieved great commercial success.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The sentence that the author placed as an epigraph to his work sums up the pedagogical and propagandist role he intended to assign to this publication: "This book is more than topical: it is urgent.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In this account, the writer warns his reader against a probable and prophetic return of a coup d'État, assimilating the one carried out by Louis-Napoléon Bonaparte twenty-six years earlier to establish the Empire to the initiative of President Mac Mahon.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Certain passages of the work are reprinted in republican newspapers but also conservative, monarchist or Bonapartist ones, each seeking to derive the best profit from it.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Other renowned writers refer to the Seize Mai crisis in their works.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] This is the case of Charles Péguy in his essay *L'Argent* in 1913.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] In 1919, Marcel Proust mentions it in *In the Shadow of Young Girls in Flower* to describe the talent or opportunism of his character, the Marquis de Norpois, who managed to play an important role before and after this date.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] She refers to a genuine "clandestine opposition culture" that sought to discredit the conservatives and more particularly President Mac Mahon, sometimes likened to a "pig", mocked for his age or his Irish origins which would make him a traitor to the nation.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] These spontaneous acts follow a topographical logic.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Susanna Barrows estimates that "faced with the moral pretensions of the regime, its adversaries took malicious pleasure in denigrating it in a scabrous, often obscene and deliberately immoral manner".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The historian sees in this proliferation of gestures or acts of derision a response to the massive purge undertaken by the government which manifests itself in a form of "brief and often scathing joke" where coarse or even scatological humour is often highlighted.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Susanna Barrows notes that "the nickname Macmoncon for Mac-Mahon spread.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Posters were put up in urinals or whispered at café counters baroque sexual scenarios featuring the president, his wife, high ecclesiastics and monarchist ministers".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] On another level, to qualify their adversaries, some republicans coined the word "seizemayeux", which Lucien Rigaud defines in his *Dictionnaire d'argot moderne* as the "nickname given to officials after 16 May, to the partisans of the reactionary policy of 16 May 1877".
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The term became established in the political slang of the Third Republic and was embodied after the crisis in the character of Oscar Seizemayeux, a little hunchbacked, one-eyed and toothless man, drawn by the caricaturist André Gill in issue no.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] 25 of the satirical weekly *La Petite Lune*.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] It is inspired by a famous imaginary comic character in the 1830s under the July Monarchy, Mayeux, created by the caricaturist Traviès, and bears the same first name as the Minister of the Interior of the de Broglie cabinet, Oscar Bardi de Fourtou, a figure hated by the entire republican group.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The number of the 363 republicans who signed the manifesto of 18 June immediately acquired great symbolic value, so that propaganda objects were quickly put into circulation.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] The portraits of the 363 as well as the printed text of the manifesto appear in particular on handkerchiefs, some of which are preserved in the National Archives or at the Bibliothèque nationale de France.
[src:1877/16-may-1877-crisis-p02] Furthermore, in 1878, Aristide Bruant composed a song entitled *Les 363 ou les vendanges de la République*.
[src:1877/1800] February 18), when the Julian calendar acknowledged a leap day and the Gregorian calendar did not, the Julian calendar fell one day farther behind, bringing the difference to 12 days until February 28 (O.S.
